{
  "doc_id": "37748",
  "text": "The earliest case occurred during an outbreak of histoplasmosis in Indianapolis in 1980. [CITATION_1] Diagnosis of disseminated histoplasmosis was made by positive urinary Histoplasma antigen. H. capsulatum and MAI were isolated from multiple organs at autopsy. The patient was presumed to have acquired histoplasmosis in Indianapolis during the second Indianapolis outbreak. [CITATION_2] The concomitant diagnosis of AIDS was first considered when cases began to be recognized in Indianapolis in 1983. AIDS was the predisposing condition in about one-third of cases of culture-proven histoplasmosis during a third Indianapolis outbreak in 1988. [CITATION_3] A study in the United States identified working with bird or bat droppings as a risk factor in patients with AIDS. [CITATION_4] Age, sex and CD4 count below 100 cells/mm [CITATION_5] were not associated with an increased risk. Recipients of antiretroviral therapy or fluconazole were protective. [CITATION_6] Another study evaluated risk factors for severe or fatal disease. Several baseline laboratory abnormalities were associated with disease severity. [CITATION_7] But multivariate analysis showed that creatinine greater than 2.1 mg/dL and albumin less than 3.5 g/dL were associated with increased risk and zidovudine therapy with decreased risk. Black race was associated with risk by univariate but not by multivariate analysis. Histoplasma antigen above 4 units was not associated with increased risk.",
